AML has several subtypes; treatment and prognosis varies among subtypes. Five-year survival varies from 15–70%, and relapse rate varies from 33–78%, depending on subtype. AML is treated initially with [[chemotherapy]] aimed at inducing a [[remission (medicine)|remission]]; patients may go on to receive additional chemotherapy or a [[hematopoietic stem cell transplant]]. Recent research into the genetics of AML has resulted in the availability of tests that can predict which drug or drugs may work best for a particular patient, as well as how long that patient is likely to survive.



